releases/0/tender/description:

Feedback from the sector, colleges in particular, told us those in first line management positions, curriculum and support staff, with job titles such as "Programme Manager", "Co-ordinator" and "Team leader" would benefit from training in management techniques. releases/0/tender/title: Supply of a Managed Print Service
releases/0/tender/description:
livin (the Client) is a Registered Social Landlord formed following the Large Scale Voluntary Transfer of local authority housing from the former Sedgefield Borough Council in 2009. The Client owns approximately 8400 homes, 2,600 garages and 60 commercial properties as well as areas of land making it one of the largest registered providers of social housing in County Durham. The Client directly employs over 130 staff based in purpose built office accommodation on the new DurhamGate site in Spennymoor.
Currently the client has a managed print service that provides three mono MFDs and two colour MFDs. All devices have several paper trays and will print both A4 and A3. These are leased with quarterly billing and there is a per page charge that covers all consumables except paper and staples. All maintenance and necessary parts are also covered under these costs.
The client is looking for a company to provide a new managed print service with features such as follow-me printing, scanning, photocopying, and auditing and accounting. This will include the lease of several multi-function devices as well as the management of the consumables and maintenance of these devices.

releases/0/tender/description:
4 contracts have been awarded for the continued development and growth of the ELMAG portal (ELMAG Phase 4).
ELMAG is a one stop facility for leaders and managers, providing learning and development opportunities that support leaders, managers and those involved with governance to effectively do their jobs, to progress within their careers and to meet the challenges and opportunities of the future. ELMAG was developed to meet sector demand and now provides a coherent and comprehensive overview of those opportunities in one online place.
As well as searching for and finding a range of training, mentoring opportunities and resources that will support individuals to navigate the challenges and maximise the opportunities within the education and training sector, the ELMAG portal also has the potential to be an online community of leaders, managers and those involved in governance who seek to support their own professional development and that of others; not just through training and development courses but also through peer-to-peer dialogue, networking, coaching and mentoring, reading and reflection.  The ELMAG portal was launched in July 2015 and the Foundation aim to ensure its continued development and growth as a valuable resource to the sector.

releases/0/tender/title: Maintenance and support of the Excellence in Leadership, Management and Governance (ELMAG) portal
releases/0/tender/description:
A contract has been awarded for the maintenance and support of the Excellence in Leadership, Management and Governance (ELMAG) portal.
The objective of ELMAG was to provide learning and development opportunities that support all types of leaders - existing, new to leadership, aspiring leaders and those involved in governance (non-executive leaders) to effectively do their jobs, to progress within their careers and to meet the challenges and opportunities of the future, and to provide a coherent and comprehensive overview of those opportunities in one online place.
As well as searching for and finding a range of training, mentoring and resources that will support individuals to navigate the challenges and maximise the opportunities within the education and training sector, the ELMAG portal is an online community of leaders, managers and those involved in governance who seek to support their own professional development and that of others; not just through training and development courses but also through peer-to-peer dialogue, networking, coaching and mentoring, reading and reflection.
The ELMAG portal was launched in July 2015, and with our delivery partners, we want to ensure its continued development and growth will enable it to be a valuable resource to the sector. The portal can be found on www.elmag.org.uk.
The portal was upgraded, with a new look to the site and improved functionality.  A delivery partner was sought to maintain the existing ELMAG portal including improvements to it. The site will maintain high quality content; be user-friendly and intuitive but with support available for visitors as well as partners who post course information on the portal. The undertaking of a quality assurance function will also be provided.
The end users of the ELMAG portal are leaders and managers mainly working in the post-16 education and training sector including small providers and third sector organisations.

releases/0/tender/title: Maths and English Pipeline IV: Building expertise to improve outcomes in maths and English
releases/0/tender/description:
The Foundation aims to drive up standards in maths and English for all learners, in line with Ofsted's focus on the importance of consistently good or better teaching, learning and assessment, and the current government policy to drive up standards in maths and English.
6 contracts were awarded by the Foundation to build on its current Continuous Professional Development (CPD) programme offered through the Maths and English Pipelines 1, 2 and 3, which in turn will build on the maths and English Enhancement Programmes, which provide a combination of resources and training for Functional Skills and GCSE teachers in maths and English as well as vocational teachers.
At the heart of effective practice in these subjects is strong and effective leadership.  This tender was built on the Foundation's existing work to support leadership and management.
Within the context of the apprenticeship reforms and the government's target to deliver 3 million apprentices by 2020, our Future Apprenticeships programme will help managers, teachers, trainers, leaders and those involved in governance to make the transition from apprenticeship frameworks to delivery of the new apprenticeship standards.
As part of this work, there will be development and delivery of a range of courses to support practitioners to embed maths and English in the new apprenticeship standards. The courses will support teachers and trainers from a range of providers across the sector on how to work closely with employers, sub-contractors and learners for effective maths and English provision. They will support practitioners to tailor learning to individuals in their industry and training context.
Pipeline IV will work with the sector to support improvements in the quality of teaching and learning in maths and English from entry levels to GCSE and beyond in a range of settings (including further education colleges, independent training providers, workplaces, community learning, third sector and offender learning).  In particular we wish to see marked improvements in the delivery of teaching and in learners' motivation and achievement in:
- maths and English Functional Skills
- maths and English in vocational subjects, including apprenticeship standards
- GCSE maths and English.

releases/0/tender/title: BBO : Reaching Out Across Durham : Programme Evaulation.
releases/0/tender/description:
The Opportunity
Groundwork NE & Cumbria is seeking a partner to undertake a mixed methods programme evaluation of ROAD: Reaching Out Across Durham.
Context
Building Better Opportunities sees the Big Lottery Fund matching funds from European Social Fund (ESF) 2014-2020, to provide joint investment in local projects that tackle poverty and promote social inclusion and drive local jobs and growth.
 
ESIF strategy for the North East LEP area

The North East LEP area's European Structural and Investment Fund Strategy for 2014 - 2020 identifies strategic weaknesses for the region to address. 

Amongst them are:

•	Employment and inclusion 
•	Skills 
•	Enterprise rates 
•	Digital connectivity 
The strategy recognises that 'employment is the key route to combating poverty and exclusion' and points out the relatively high levels of unemployment and economic inactivity
Groundwork NE & Cumbria is the lead partner for BBO in County Durham.  Working with 11 voluntary and community sector delivery partners Reaching Out Across Durham (ROAD) will target 625 of the hardest to reach and provide them with intensive support and advice to help them move towards employment and or training.  ROAD will also develop new services that our participant's will be able to access including health, financial and digital inclusion activities as well as supporting them to access existing services
The Programme will run until July 2019.

releases/0/tender/title: Wigan Council Sexual Health Market Testing Event
releases/0/tender/description:
Wigan Council has an ambitious programme of growth and reform and clear aspirations to make Wigan a place that people want to live, work, invest and visit, where we improve life opportunities and independence for all people to start, live and age well. To do this we have set out a strategy for public service reform and improved health and wellness that is built on an asset based approach to working with communities called the Deal for the Future.

Phase one of our sexual health consultation ran from December 2016 to January 2017. We consulted with over 300 people including members of the public, service providers and key partners on the current sexual health services and the opportunities for a new service.  This included consultation on service areas such as location, delivery in the community, opening times and use of technology.  A summary of the findings can be viewed alongside this advert or available at the link below.

We are currently in phase two of the consultation. We are consulting on a proposed model for sexual health services and would welcome your views as a potential provider of sexual health services in Wigan. More detailed information can be found here: 

https://www.wigan.gov.uk/Council/Consultations/Current/Sexual-health-review.aspx 

In addition, we will be using this event as an opportunity to make providers aware of the forthcoming procurement process for sexual health services in Wigan, and enable providers to raise any questions they may have of Commissioners. Providers attending the event will also be supported to identify opportunities for collaborative delivery of services where this may be appropriate.

This event also provides an opportunity for potential providers to work with stakeholders in the Borough to discuss some specific aspects of the proposed model, including the offer in relation to; Primary Care, Schools, Digital and Vulnerable Groups. 

Please complete the form below if you would like to attend the sexual health stakeholder provider event.  Forms must be returned no later than Friday 28th April.  Restrictions to 2 persons per provider may be applied if over subscribed.

A list of the properties on the programme can be found In 'Section 3 - Priced Tender Summary'.

Additional information: 
We have introduced a new electronic tendering system called CSW-JETS (Coventry, Solihull and Warwickshire's Joint E-Tendering System). In order for you to do business with us in the future you must register on the system by following the link below and then clicking the 'register here' button. 

www.csw-jets.co.uk

CSW-JETS is the new sub-regional e-tendering portal run by In-tend.  Since February 2010, Coventry, Solihull, Warwickshire, Nuneaton & Bedworth and Rugby Councils have been working together as a shared procurement service. Along with Solihull Community Housing, we have joined together to bring you a collaborative E-Tendering portal. 

CSW-JETS enables us to advertise our opportunities across all authorities through the same system. This means that there is a single point of contact for procurement in the sub-region so you only have to register once to receive notifications for all authorities. Registering on the portal will make it easier for local suppliers to find, respond to and be alerted to tender opportunities. 

Registration is free, and takes just a few minutes. When complete, you will be able to express interest in any of the Councils'/Authorities' opportunities when they are made available. In addition, we will be able to access your details whenever we have a requirement, and you may then be invited to tender or quote for work.

releases/0/tender/description:
DETAILED INFORMATION CAN BE FOUND IN THE CONTRACT NOTICE WHICH IS PROVIDED AS AN ATTACHMENT
Crown Commercial Service, as the Contracting Authority, is putting in place a Pan Government Framework Agreement, for the duration of 3 years plus 1, for the provision of managed learning services for use by UK public sector bodies identified at paragraph VI.3  of the Contract Notice (attached), and any future successors to these organisations, which include:Central Government Departments and their Arm's Length Bodies and Agencies;  Non Departmental Public Bodies;  NHS bodies and Local Authorities.
The above mentioned Public Sector Bodies have a need for the appointment of a single prime contractor, or a consortium
with a lead supplier acting as prime contractor, to work in effective partnership with participating organisations by providing access to a range of high quality learning and development services and
solutions designed to meet the needs of the Civil Service and UK public sector bodies, on a managed service basis. This procurement relates to the Administrative social, educational, healthcare and cultural services which are listed in Schedule 3 of the Public Contracts Regulations 2015 (PCR) 2015 as a specific service.

This procurement is being conducted under the Light Touch Regime ('LTR') and will be conducted in accordance with regulations 74 to 76 PCR 2015 in the style of the open procedure.
The procurement will be conducted in three (3) stages which will be run consecutively. Full details are available in the Invitation to Tender which can be accessed at: https://gpsesourcing.cabinetoffice.gov.uk
using the instructions detailed in paragraph III.2.1. of the Contract Notice (attached).
Although this procurement is being run under the Light Touch Regime, the Authority has chosen to observe a Standstill Period. Following a Standstill Period of ten (10) calendar days and subject to there being no substantive challenge to the Intention to Award, a Framework Agreement will be formally awarded.

Additional information: Candidates will be assessed in accordance with Section 5 of the 2015 Public Contract Regulations (implementing the Directive) on the basis of information provided in response to an Invitation to Tender ("ITT"). 
This procurement will be managed electronically via the Crown Commercial Service's e-Sourcing Suite. To participate in this procurement, participants must first be registered on the e-Sourcing Suite. If you have not yet registered on the eSourcing Suite, this can be done online at https:// gpsesourcing.cabinetoffice.gov.uk by following the link 'Register for CCS eSourcing'. Please note that, to register, you must have a valid DUNS number (as provided by Dun and Bradstreet) for the organisation which you are registering, who will be entering into a contract if invited to do so. Full instructions for registration and use of the system can be found at
https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/esourcing-tool-guidance-for-suppliers
Once you have registered on the eSourcing Suite, a registered user can express an interest for a specific procurement. This is done by emailing expressionofinterest@crowncommercial.gov.uk
Your email must clearly state: the name and reference for the procurement you wish to register for; the name of the registered supplier; and the name and contact details for the registered individual sending the email. Crown Commercial Service will process the email and then enable the supplier to access the procurement online via the e-Sourcing Suite. The registered user will receive a notification email to alert them once this has been done.
As a user of the e-Sourcing Suite you will have access to the Emptoris messaging service which facilitates all messages sent to you and from you in relation to any specific RFX event. Please note it is your responsibility to access these messages on a regular basis to ensure you have sight of all relevant information.
For technical assistance on use of the e-Sourcing Suite please contact Crown Commercial Service Support Desk email: eEnablement@crowncommercial.gov.uk
Responses must be published by the date in paragraph IV.3.4. of the Contract Notice (attached).
Potential suppliers should note that, in accordance with the UK Government's policies on transparency, Crown Commercial Service intends to publish the Invitation to Tender (ITT) document and the text of any Framework Agreement awarded, subject to possible redactions at the discretion of Crown Commercial Service. The Authority and other contracting bodies utilising the Framework reserve the right to use any electronic portal during the life of the agreement.
Important Notes:
a) all stated Contract values are estimates only. Suppliers are not guaranteed business through this Framework Agreement;
b) the Authority has the option of extending the Framework Agreement  for a further year beyond the "Contract end date" stated in this Notice.

releases/0/tender/title: Health and Justice Expert Panel Delivering effective lived experience insight to Health and Justice Team (East Midlands)
releases/0/tender/description:
NHS England is sourcing a Provider for a Health and Justice Expert Panel within Prisons, SARCs Liaison & Diversion (L&D), Immigration Removal Centre, Secure Training Centres and Children's Homes within the East Midlands region. The Health and Justice team are looking to work with a partner who has access to a cross section of the community who have experience across the criminal justice pathway who will provide an Expert panel that will inform the commissioning decisions that we make to procure services. The Expert Panel will provide lived experience into the Health and Justice Team, as part of the Health and Justice Panel there will be an expectation to have attendance at a conference to support and highlight the patient/service user voice. The provider will have access to a range of individuals who will form the Health and Justice Expert Panel; they will also be trained in both influencing and governance and providing effective lived expertise to act as a supportive mechanism to policy and practice decision making when commissioning services. NHS England requires a H&J Lived Experience Panel who have experience of the criminal justice system and can participate in discussions where they will use their experiences to inform the discussion. This discussion will in turn inform our procurement decisions. If you are interested in this quotation exercise, please contact Sarah Groves, Procurement Administrator, by emailing sarah.groves@ardengemcsu.nhs.uk 
Quotations are required by 12 noon on Wednesday 26th April 2017.

Additional information: Please apply directly to the buyer using the contact details provided.

releases/0/tender/title: Liverpool Pier Head Summer Animation (Concession Contract)
releases/0/tender/description:
Liverpool City Council are inviting proposal from interested parties to produce an animation and entertainment offer to Liverpool's World UNESCO Heritage site of the Pier Head in the summer of 2017. 

It is hoped that this activity will create a tourism destination which will attract the people of Liverpool and beyond, allowing them to witness an incredible fusion of culture which will exceed public expectation and an increased footfall to the area. 

Specifically the aims of this exercise:-
•	To provide a celebration of the City's unique waterfront public realm
•	To further develop the reputation of Liverpool as a key cultural and visitor destination with a host of high quality cultural events.
•	To deliver a high quality summer programme
•	To attract local, regional and national visitors to the City, especially staying visitors.
•	To link the Albert Dock to the attractions on the Pier Head and in Cunard Building 
•	To create a standalone visitor destination during the summer months which amplifies the waterfront

This allows users to easily access their favourite SharePoint folders from within Outlook so they can 'drag and drop' email and attachments from inbox/sent items into SharePoint, thus helping the management of mailbox sizes and ensuring that important evidential emails are stored in SharePoint (hence ensuring compliance with Public Records Act, FOI/EIR acts. releases/0/tender/description: Provision of supported bus service contracts in Merseyside with contract periods up to 23/07/18, 1 year with a provisional start date of 23/07/17

Bus operators are required to register local bus services with the Traffic Commissioner at least 56 days prior to the commencement of a new service or of a service change. At the same time that the operator applies to register the service, they are required to provide a copy of the registration to any local authority within which the service will operate.

On receipt of the registration, Leicestershire County Council (LCC) input the details on to its route and timetable management system. The registration data is then uploaded to the server of the Traveline website to ensure the most up to date public transport travel information is always available to the public.

The contract for the current management system has now come to an end. LCC is now looking to retender for a management system to oversee the bus route and timetable data for all bus services within Leicestershire, with the ability to monitor and update service frequencies and changes to service provision
For further information please visit our procurement portal; https://www.eastmidstenders.org

releases/0/tender/title: Refurbishment of the Main Hall Roof at Bembridge Primary School
releases/0/tender/description:
The Isle of Wight Council invited quotes from suitably qualified providers for the refurbishment of the main hall roof at Bembridge Primary School. The contract is to run from 10 April 2017 for a period of six weeks completing on 19 May 2016. 

A brief summary of the work is detailed below:

•	The contractor is to set up the necessary scaffolding / roof access to allow for the refurbishment of the main hall roof in a safe and correct manner. 
•	The existing uPVC fascia and hopper outlets are to be removed and replaced with new. The existing perimeter upstand to the roof is to be built up to allow for an increase in insulation. 
•	The existing roof surface is to be cleaned, all cracks repaired/filled before it is then prepared / primed as necessary to accept new built up felt roofing system complete with flat rigid board insulation. 
•	New uPVC fascia is to be fitted on all sides of the roof. The new roof finish is to terminate on the north and south side to the new aluminium hopper outlets. New down pipes are to be supplied on the north and south side of the roof (two outlets per side).

Additional information: The procurement will be managed using the South East Business Portal. The registration process is free. Simple and full instructions on how to do this are available on the South East Business Portal. Once your registration is confirmed, you will receive a username and password via email. When you log on for the first time you will be prompted to change your password. Please note however that if your company has already been registered, your application will be rejected to avoid duplication and additional service users will need to be set up on the existing account. There is no cost to you for registering your company.

releases/0/tender/description:
Influenza virus infection of mammalian host species, especially pigs, represents a human and animal health risk because of the ability of influenza viruses to undergo reassortment, antigenic shift and drift that can lead to the emergence of new variants and strains with pandemic potential. It is particularly important to understand the host factors that influence these viral mutation and adaptation events. This studentship project aims to identify porcine host correlates of infection at the gene expression level. There are several likely candidate genes, mostly from the interferon immune response pathway. However, in some cases, it is unknown whether genes are relevant in the porcine host even though they have been demonstrated to be important during influenza virus infection of other host species or models (humans, mice and others).  The main aim of this work will therefore be to establish new protocols or apply existing methods to verify the choice of target genes and test them on in vitro models and recently archived in vivo materials.

releases/0/tender/description:
EVALUATE A NEW SOCIAL PRESCRIBING PILOT IN THE LONDON BOROUGH OF MERTON OVER A 12 MONTH PERIOD 

The London Borough of Merton Public Health is looking to engage an organisation, agency or consultant to undertake a 12 month formative evaluation of a Social Prescribing pilot programme. 

London Borough of Merton has embarked on an exciting pilot social prescribing programme in order to explore this approach as part of the primary care transformation underway in the borough. Social prescribing is a way of linking patients in primary care with sources of support within the community. The initiative expands the options available in consultations, creating a coordinated way for primary care services to refer patients with social, emotional and/or practical needs to a variety of local non-clinical services such as leisure, social activities, education, welfare, housing and employment.

A full statement of the requirements under the proposed contract appears in section 2 of this Request for Quotation (RFQ) pack, through the Council's E-Tendering system ProContract:
https://www.londontenders.org/portal/CMS.nsf/vHomePage/fSection?OpenDocument

releases/0/tender/description:
Medicines are the most frequently utilised healthcare intervention in the NHS. The Prescribing and Medicines Optimisation (PMO) Service supports customers, including Clinical Commissioning Groups (CCG), NHS England, acute trusts, local authorities and community health trusts, to ensure that medicines are commissioned and prescribed in a safe, legal, evidence based and cost effective way. Medicines optimisation is concerned with maximising quality, outcomes and value for patients from the medicines that they take; it extends into all aspects of the pathway from the prescriber to the patient, to the pharmacy or dispensing practice and encompasses all of the health and social care professionals that may be involved in that patients care.  
The Pharmaceutical Needs Assessment (PNA) is a statutory document that assesses the pharmacy needs of the local population. This includes dispensing services as well as public health and other services that pharmacies may provide. The document is used as the framework for commissioning pharmacy services in a defined area. There is a statutory requirement for each local authority's Health and Wellbeing Boards (HWB) to produce a PNA every three years.

releases/0/tender/title: NHS North Norfolk, Norwich and South Norfolk Clinical Commissioning Group Community Vasectomy Service AQP
releases/0/tender/description:
NHS North Norfolk, South Norfolk and Norwich CCGs are procuring a community vasectomy service for the population of the Central Norfolk Area using the Any Qualified Provider (AQP) route. 

The aim is to provide a high quality community vasectomy service. This will ensure patients have choice and ease of access and to meet the overall objectives of delivering care closer to home. 

In securing services from Any Qualified Providers (AQP), the CCGs require assurance of competence, quality and safety standards, just as it would for services secured under a formal tender process. 

Any provider will be eligible to apply for this AQP subject to demonstrating compliance and competency against the specified criteria outlined in the service specification. 

Aims and objectives of service

The aim of the service is to provide those patients who wish to have a vasectomy under Local Anaesthetic the choice of having their counselling and procedure undertaken within a local primary or community care setting at a time convenient to them. 

The objectives of the service are:

To provide high quality, cost effective, local community vasectomy services.

To provide services that comply with accepted best practice in line with national and local guidance, relevant accreditations processes, relevant guidelines in clinical practice and robust governance arrangements.

releases/0/tender/title: PI1300739 - Bicameral Stock Control and Purchasing System
releases/0/tender/description:
The Corporate Officer of the House of Lords and the Corporate Officer of the House of Commons (the Authority), invite you to submit a tender for the services as detailed in this Invitation to Tender (ITT) and the various requirements documents. 
      
      The Houses of Parliament is looking to award a new contract on behalf of the House of Lords Catering & Retail Service and the House Commons Catering Service for a Bicameral Stock Control & Purchasing System. This is to meet the corporate objective of both Houses of Parliament for providing value for money in the delivery of their catering services, through effective and efficient inventory management. Each House is a legal entity in its own right and outlets are owned by one or the other House, not jointly.
      
      Revenue for both House of Commons' and House of Lords' operations is forecast to be over ?13 million in the financial year 2016/17, with total annual covers/transactions estimated at over 1.5 million. In total, the two organisations employ around 400 staff. The stock control and purchasing system will be expected to serve the operational requirements of over 30 venues within five separate sites across the Parliamentary Estate, including the Palace of Westminster.
      
      There is some commonality between the catering ICT systems currently in use in both houses. In the case of Electronic Point of Sale (EPOS) this is Micros 3700 RES 5.4 and Artifax Event 4.2.0.21 for Banqueting and Events Management.
      
      There is currently no common stock management and purchasing system, and the Houses of Parliament is therefore seeking a solution that serves the catering departments in both Houses. Any solution should provide integration with the current EPOS and financial systems.
      
      Currently the catering department in the House of Commons uses Check SCM 3.5 as a Stock Management tool for stock control and purchasing.  The House of Lords catering department does not have any Stock Management system for managing food and all processes are manual using spreadsheets. Beverages and souvenirs are managed using Micros Material control.
      
      o Each House has its own finance system (Agresso) using different cost centre and General Ledger code structures. 
      o We are seeking a solution that can integrate with the existing EPOS and Events Management systems as well as interfacing with each houses finance system. 
      o We are seeking a system that will support both catering departments. In view of the above arrangements, the Houses of Parliament is flexible regarding your proposal; whether this is through two instances of the same system with the ability to be merged at a later stage, or one system to be used by both organisations. 
      
      The Authority is seeking a commercial 'off-the shelf' (COTS) solution; a bespoke solution would not meet the Houses of Parliament's ICT strategic goals. Any added development required to meet the requirements in the ITT should be offered as part of the standard produ...

Additional information: The Houses of Parliament wish to give notice of a potential contract opportunity on behalf of their respective Catering Departments for a Bicameral Stock Control & Purchasing System. This is to meet the corporate objective of both Houses (Commons and Lords) for providing value for money in the delivery of their catering services through effective and efficient inventory management. Each House is a separate entity in its own right and outlets are owned by one or the other House, not jointly.

If you are interested in this potential opportunity and would like to be kept informed, please submit your expression of interest via our In-Tend procurement portal (https://in-tendhost.co.uk/parliamentuk/aspx/Home) by responding to this Prior Information Notice (listed within Tenders > Current).

Please note that the deadline for expressions of interest is 10:00 hours UK time on Monday 20th of February 2017.

releases/0/tender/title: Maintenance of A Pea Gene Bank
releases/0/tender/description:
Objectives of the project include:

1) To maintain and characterise the 3565 accessions within the pea collection. To manage the collection by dealing with new introductions and their characterisation (30-50 per year) and the regeneration of older accessions and stocks in need of multiplication.

2) To maintain and update associated passport and characterisation databases associated with the collection including stock management, passport and characterisation files. Also includes the revision of existing data and the collation of new information/data as it becomes available.

3) To develop and facilitate access to the collection via the development of web based
documentation, searchable databases.

4) To promote and enhance awareness of the collection by exploiting new media technologies such as videos and QR code labeling and through growing demonstrations of reference material from the collection for researchers and breeders to observe at first hand the variation within the collection.

5) To further develop resources linked to the recent molecular marker diversity analysis coupled with targeted characterisation of germplasm based on priority traits as identified by researchers and industry.
